it took me longer than i wanted to get this out because it took me time to get through surviving r kelly. it was hard to watch. i encourage you to watch it. i lived in miami when the initial video of him urinating on that young girl came out. i found out about it because i was in a gay club on south beach and they played the fucking video remixed with his music. i could not believe it. that shit stuck with me forever. i thought to myself - well at least thatâ€™s the end of his career right? ha! thatâ€™s not how it works in a patriarchy especially when wrapped in capitalism. as long as you can still make people money - you are still valuable. exploit and abuse women - no problem. exploit and abuse young black women - even less of a problem. thatâ€™s the reality of what we are seeing so clearly illustrated right now. pay attention to how it works...this is how we start to dismantle it. fuck r kelly. his studio is in chicago (at 219 n justine street). people know him. heâ€™s around town. just living his life. folks are holding #muterkelly protests at his studio. the police are investigating because they believe some of the women are being held there. #muterkelly #blm #blacklivesmatter #patriarchy #capitalism #feminism #feminist #craftivism #craftivist #badasscrossstitch #resist #metoo #timeisup

text: i believe i am near the end of posting all 76-ish of my previous art to ig. i found this #acrylic #painting in the january 2017 folder so, thatâ€™s when i #painted it. this is a #powerful #female #warrior, a #shield #maiden or a #knight centering herself prior to #battle. think the #ladies canâ€™t be #badass? let me gently direct your attention to the soviet army of ww2, the viet cong of the 60â€™s, the modern israeli army, and the us military; all of whom have accomplished combat veterans. badassery isnâ€™t limited to the killing fields either. thereâ€™s the courage of #metoo , the women of local police forces, and teachers, who must daily deal with our community spawn. but i digress. the use of #blue, #violet, and #red seems to have become my schtick. the blue lips? who knows what i was thinking. anyway, #portraits arenâ€™t in demand so the #artwork was relegated to the #dustbin of #history, aka my closet, relatively quickly. the #sirens i paint are not actual #people, mind you. they are an amalgam of various interesting souls i see, whether on tv, in the kino, on the street, etc. why? i suck at #realism. anywho, if you like my portrait work, give a like or comment and iâ€™ll keep doing them occasionally; otherwise, plants and animals are much, much more interesting. have a cosmic day.

"for the first time in its 127-year history, the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys â€” and the document features a warning.
â€œtraditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit malesâ€™ psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health,â€ the report warns.

the new â€œguidelines for psychological practice with boys and menâ€ defines â€œmasculinity ideologyâ€ as â€œa particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewal of the appearance of weakness.â€ the report links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part, too. he recommended they let their boys know, â€œitâ€™s ok to not be ok all the time.â€'
--tim fitzsimons, @nbcnews

put this book on your radar immediately. i usually find myself not finishing the free books i find for my kindle, but found myself unable to put this one down. the forgotten hours does not disappoint. this is definitely a heavy read that rings the #metoo bell. a few times.
â€¢
the story follows katie, a 20-something new yorker, navigating her life as her father is about to be released from prison. years before, when katie was a teen, her father was accused of a terrible crime involving her best friend. the story goes back and forth from present day, to katieâ€™s own memory of events. she also begins to realize how much of the truth of what happened was kept from her, so she begins to do some digging herself.
â€¢
schumann is a really talented writer. i loved the memories katie had of summers on the lake with her best friend. schumann really tapped into what itâ€™s like inside a teenâ€™s head. most of the scenes of katie in present day show her as being very introspective. i wish she had interacted more with her mother and brother, the few parts where the story dragged could have been easily pushed along by a phone call. in fact, i think a lot could have been added to the story if we had heard more from katieâ€™s mother and how the events really impacted her.
â€¢
4/5 stars.

text:
one of the most effectual things you can do to help get #basicincome adopted more quickly in your country is to activate existing organizations to start fighting for it to better achieve their own mission statements.

food banks canada understands that people need ubi for food security. the canadian medical association understands that people need ubi to live healthier lives with less need for medical interventions. vancouver rape relief understands that women need ubi to better escape and avoid abusive relationships. the list goes on, but the list is not long enough, not long enough by far. 
whatever organization you are part of, ask yourself how ubi will help your org better achieve its mission. do what you can to make sure your org or an org whose mission you care about starts fighting for ubi!

text:
there was a time where i used to hope to lose my memory or erase what happened to me. i thought of myself as see through, and like a statistic. today, i am more than that. i am not a victim anymore, but a survivor. today, i can help people who are going through what i went through. today i can empower others.  today, i can show others that there is hope for a better future. today, i can say that i have a strength i never had. now, i am not happy about the memories from the past - but they don't have power over me or effect me the way it did in the first few years of healing. let yourself feel, and let yourself heal. .
.
.
.
.

text:
all of us experience the world through our own lens or filter. what we experience depends on our beliefs, our perception of what and how we see and hear, and how we project ourselves through our writing. 
i invite you to take part in this 4 week online course, where we will gently discover what we unconsciously relate to in the world, how we feel about those relationships and what they have caused us to believe about ourselves and others. we will then use those discoveries to see how we would like to view those things differently. we will transform our unconscious beliefs from negative to positive and begin to see amazing results in how we move about the world in our thinking and actions.

recordings will be made available to all registered participants. if you are unable to attend all 4 sessions at the time listed, no worries! you can listen to the recordings at your convenience and still get the benefits you need from each repatterning.

we are all plants, ready to be nourished, ready to grow.  let's unravel what no longer serves us, nourish our new thought patterns, and grow together. *online series february 25-march 18, 9:30-11:00 am pst
**investment $100 for the series
bonus: 10% off your personal session when you book the series

you don't have to be a feminist to respect females. you can still believe in chivalry or recognize there are gender differences to know that women are not inferior. the other side of the coin, you don't have to be a female to be a feminist, men can too. on a social level we should be deemed as equal for our rights, and recognize that our genetic make up makes us different. without men, women cannot conceive. without women, men cannot implant a seed. 
one cannot exist without the other, and there should be no argument about the superior gender because it's equally yin and yang. .

text:
"and i also find it hard to think that when, as a woman, i say no, my no should be different from that of a man. because if a woman says no to a man who harasses her, there is always, always, always the conviction that she has been looking for, that in the end it was her fault. because when the finger indicates the pig, there is always someone who sees the woman and calls her a whore, because maybe she was wearing provocative clothes, because she was alone around three in the night, because if you make three mojitos then you can not pretend. so, let's see if the message arrives...when a woman says no, it's no. she could have said yes to 99 men and you are the hundredth, and it is "no" anyway, at any age, anywhere and at any rate of ethyl. actually, if she is drunk and you harass her, you're even more asshole. nobody gives you the right to touch her, to abuse her and rape her just because you are bigger, stronger or have more power".
.
.

text:
content warning!
could be a little triggering for some as i talk about struggling after domestic violence

a friend of mind dropped off some pink/purple  roses for me because he noticed i've been struggling lately. what a nice little surprise! 
i was struggling, i've been having some battles in my head, trying to figure out where my life is going and what it has become. 
my abuser is gone, but is he really? 
i'm afraid not, for because of the abuse, because of the countless punches and kicks, the names, the rape, losing my children... he's still here.... he's in every man who flirts with me
he's in every man who tells me i'm beautiful
he's in every man that touches me
he's in every truck i see
he's in smells i smell
he's in the bangs in the night

he's in my nightmares... i try not to give it power but it seems the more i resist the stronger they get. i wake up sweating, panicked and crying, i have to get out of bed and search my house thinking he's hiding in the closets, check my windows and doors ensuring they're locked. 
he's not gone... he's still here
he's become a part of who i am, of how i live. 
i don't know how long i'll be in trauma counseling, nor do i know if this will end up in a diagnosis.

what i do know, is i have people around who i can trust.

text:
the clock ticked half past two at night. i had just finished with an article and my lousy eyes were craving for sleep. then all of a sudden, the phone beeped. i pulled the notification bar to have a look at the text. it read, "hi! how have you been?"
i was quite startled. i mean who pings up for a conversation so late? the bar didn't show a name rather a number. now that was intriguing. i opened the messenger. who knew that this curiosity of mine was going to haunt me for days!

the profile picture was visible. my heart cringed. i couldn't believe it rather i didn't want to. i so badly wanted me to be wrong. finally i clicked on the picture and damn, my world went blank. my heart was racing as if in quest of searching an escape route to my mouth! after two long years of separation, i saw that smile again.

it'd been really hard for me to sideline all the memories, every little quirk that defined us, every single muse that we rhymed together, every single song which we hummed, every half-pint grief we sighed together. maybe together was a satire and our love was sabotaged. 
it took me long but i'd been able to trick my heart into not yearning for you. the indelible marks you'd carved on my soul were covered with sheaths of indifference. the scars you left had dried up into lines of nonchalance until now when you freshened up my wounds which bled melancholy.

my head was bursting. my inner core was a complete turmoil. i wanted to text back but i couldn't afford to hurt myself anymore. i had to save myself. my cheeks were burning with the continuous tears and i couldn't take it anymore.

i blocked the number and curled a sleepless night.

sourav dey.
(@quill_and_paper)
.
.

"for the first time in its 127-year history, the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys â€” and the document features a warning.
â€œtraditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit malesâ€™ psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health,â€ the report warns.

the new â€œguidelines for psychological practice with boys and menâ€ defines â€œmasculinity ideologyâ€ as â€œa particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewal of the appearance of weakness.â€ the report links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part, too. he recommended they let their boys know, â€œitâ€™s ok to not be ok all the time.â€'
--tim fitzsimons, @nbcnews

text: whatâ€™s the weirdest thing youâ€™ve had to do for a shoot? models often have to do wacky and wonderful things such as having their entire body painted, without even being told about it in advance.  their agents often agree these factors for them and may not pass on the information, so models can feel pressured to go along with such situations. it is important to ask what your job involves, have an agent you trust, make sure these products are safe to use on your skin and to ensure that you feel comfortable at all times.

text: our first #outragedenemy of #2019 is a musician plagued with lascivious rumors since the #1990s - #rkelly - he was acquitted of 21 charges of child pornography years ago, but a #bbc #documentary and new series #survivingrkelly have showed his sick history and interviewed many of his victims. #webelievethewomen and several have come forward, broken ndas, and testified that he has a proclivity for young girls, has coerced many into #sexacts and may have brainwashed a few to a kind of sex slavery. the abundant accusations are disturbing and it looks like the rumors are true and he is being investigated by the fbi. not only are the women telling their truth, but so are their parents of his cult charisma. he married singer #aaliyah (deceased) in the 1990s when she was only 15 and many other girls have said that they've had sex with him at the same age. one girl has tried suing him for spreading herpes and the stories don't stop. we only saw parts of the @lifetime doc and there's more to come. some say that kanye west is the black donald #plumpf, but it seems that the amount of allegations, victims, witnesses, and the awfulness of the acts makes it more apparent that #muterkelly is. over 20 women have accused the #clownking of #sexualassault and harrassment or even rape, but he's skated by. hopefully because of the mounting #evidence - @rkelly won't be able to. the #metoo movement has gained momentum over the last year, so we hope that its exposure will carry on to the neglected black women.

text: feminist denim jacket. made for the â€˜young bloodâ€™ project - a chance to protest something you feel passionate about. i embroidered this @weekday_stores jacket around the time of #metoo and #timesup. the large patch on the back was inspired by the placards that people take to rallies, and the patches on the arm were taken from online hashtags - as well as the red embroidery collage for #freeperiods and the appliquÃ©d nipples for #freethenipple movement. the ribbons were also to represent the straps of corsets and other restraints being thrown off. the wire fist was taken from the @all_womankind organisation, and the lily screenprint is commonly associated with the vagina (the beaded flowers were similarly chosen to represent growth and persistence). finally, the hand-sewn gold beads on the collar were to suggest chains as a hint to armour, and the hairy cuff to normalise women who choose not to shave. #whywewearblack #womensmarch #denimjacket #heforshe #effyourbeautystandards #sorrynotsorry #donttellmetosmile #costumestudent #embroidery #nastywomen #equality ğŸŒ¹âœŠğŸ»â›“

text:
sexual abuse and trauma are very real, yet they seem to be swept under the rug especially in the #blackcommunity. while i have never been sexually abused i know far too many women and men who have been. so, if you are wondering why i look so happy, it's because my friend @sharonadrake wrote an amazing book on healing from sexual trauma and i am sooooo proud of her willingness to be vulnerable. even if sexual abuse has not been your personal experience, it's important to educate yourself about it and the healing process because 1 in 5 women and 1 and 71 men have experienced it which means a friend or family member you see everyday might be dealing with this process. visit her page to get your copy now! .
.

"for the first time in its 127-year history, the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys â€” and the document features a warning.
â€œtraditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit malesâ€™ psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health,â€ the report warns.

the new â€œguidelines for psychological practice with boys and menâ€ defines â€œmasculinity ideologyâ€ as â€œa particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewal of the appearance of weakness.â€ the report links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part, too. he recommended they let their boys know, â€œitâ€™s ok to not be ok all the time.â€'
--tim fitzsimons, @nbcnews

text:
a tale afflict 
since i were a kid i was taught,
for our rights we girls always fought.

when i grew old,
i was told to be strong and bold.

my mumma told me to fight but this principle was only applicable out,
when you are home they will devour on you as you are "wine & stout". i spoke for my right,
they said you are a girl who's not supposed to fight.

i wanted them to be punished,
but before that i found myself finished.

the days i breathe, the nights i cried,
all just ended, i found myself alone though i tried.

i cried out loud,
but the way i did was just a played out sound.

i was afraid to go out,
but then found myself sold on the rate they ought.

i'm a girl,
i'm a lady,
i'm a daughter,
i'm a sister,
i'm a wife,
i'm a mother,
please treat me the way i deserve,
i'm a human like you, dont treat me something other... the_spill_ink

in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

text:
part 1 my story of living hell
good morning my people, i am conal strong wolf macphee, first born of the first born of the first born to the commander in chief of clan macphee, my clan is god's holy warriors, i was born to lead,  born to fight, i am the yin and the yang, i have the power to hate & destroy, and i have the power to love & build, here is some of my story.
i suffered much abuse as a young child, mental physical and sexual abuse. at 5 years old i started to rage, throwing chairs at kids in kindergarten, tried to fight and stab other kids at ages 5, 6 and 7, attacked kicked and punched teachers...my wrechard father who was one of the causes of the abuse(explain another time) admitted me into children's pysch hospital at 6 for anger and rage issues. god damn it!! did no one think why? why would a kid act out this way. i'll tell why; after being sexually abused since a toddler(recently i had regressive repressed memory therapy and the memories resurfaced) then i was raped by two teenage boys,  adopted brothers of my step dad, sitting in my own piss, shit and blood i begged god for the day i would kill them all and god promised me i would have retribution. they made me sleep with them, when they fell asleep i went grabbed an axe and held it over there heads ready to strike, but i didn't, i was scared, after i absolutely hated myself and wanted to die, i was so scared of my step dad, he would beat me relentlessly, he would whip me on my back with the buckle of his belt like a slave, smack and throw me around, choke me almost to death(my mom walked in just in time to save me, he was trying to kill me, i was turning blue) saddest part was i told myself i deserved it. my life was so sad. this violent & sexual abuse was a living hell. it almost killed me, almost drove me insane, and there is much more hell fire, utter saddness and torment to come, i will divulge this in part 2. i tell you this not for you to feel sorry for me, but to for you empathize & realize where my justifiable murderous rage comes from, and why my resolve is relentless..this is why i will trade my life to save one child from this living hell
#metoo

text:
completed piece from the panty project.
preparing for exhibition, the wash (as it seams) @msuunionartgallery @michiganstateu january 21 - march 9, 2019
.
"panty portrait: beef curtains" from the panty project, 14 of 51
.

fiber art, archival pigment print on museum cotton rag, 19 x 14 inches .
the panty project is an ongoing social practice project. participants, womxn and those who identify as womxn, courageously share with me their stories of experienced gendered transgressions and violent aggressions, whether cultural and/or interpersonal. participants write a word or phrase onto the panel of their selected undergarment; i hand-embroider over their mark-making and photograph them as if they have been taken off. this work addresses the inherent misogyny within our language, and the consequential "essestializing" of womxn, which reduces womxn, and those who identify as womxn, to "less than." this work is about healing and transcendence. 
womxn's long-silenced voices must be heard.
.

i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
why does society ask the victim "well why didn't you leave? usually when a domestic violence incident occurs, this person has shown you "the best side of them" in the beginning, and you stay to work to get back to that act. but, they test them in the beginning on what they can get away with - to the point where the victim can no longer decipher what is abuse or if it's "discipline" without realizing they should not be disciplined by their equal. before you say anything about the victim, try and understand what's going through the mind of a victim.

text:
i would like to introduce to you, my new blog. the word â€˜shineâ€™ has a few different meanings in my life right now and seemed appropriate to include it in this part of my journey too.
.
i am just a normal girl trying to empower women, in any way i can. so iâ€™ll be using this blog, to share my life experiences, along with other day to day life events like recipes, beauty tips, fashion and fitness.
.
i have come to realize, especially with whats been going on lately that â€œme tooâ€ is relevant in all aspects of life. i love that the me too movement has become so big and given people an opportunity to speak out about abuse, and i want this blog to be an opportunity to start a conversation too, about whatever it is you need a â€œme tooâ€ about. i want you to feel safe in whatever is going on in your world and know youâ€™re not alone. why do we get that security when you learn that someone else is going through what youâ€™re going through; good or bad? .
.
i want to share things that have gone on in my life, the good the bad and the ugly. i want whoever is reading this to feel the â€˜me tooâ€™ they need right now. whether that be a â€œgirl, sameâ€ with a high five, or a â€œthis also happened to meâ€ while grabbing for the tissues. either way, i feel the need to bare all, blog by blog, so here we go.
.
so iâ€™d love it if you could head over and have a read and give us a follow. link in bio.

text:
we attended an event yesterday and a woman who had been a victim of sex trafficking and then actually became a trafficker herself explained that she used to go to church to "shop for new victims". she said she would spend several sundays in a row at the same church watching to see who seemed troubled, who went to the altar each week, and who talked about or appeared to have an unmet need. she would then go in for the kill by befriending them and "meeting their need". they trusted her because after all they met in church! within a month, she said she would have them under her control and "out on the track". this was girls and guys...
we cannot emphasize enough that you cannot be so trusting of others, even in church, especially in church!! predators love to insinuate themselves into spaces where they can exploit people's needs and pain, and church is the perfect place. they simply need to look and dress the part and mimic the behaviors of the environment, and they are generally accepted without question or true vetting. that being said, watch your children and young adults closely, even at church. don't give church members or leaders access to your children and young adults.  because when you come to present yourself in the house of the lord, satan come also looking to see whom he could devour! #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate #volunteer #family

text:
i saw "gloria: a life" last night and it ignited a flame i've been dancing around with the #metoo moment this past year. so much so i found myself with a microphone in my hand during our audience talking circle and it inspired me to write:
---------------
there is a moment 
when something happens
to you
and you freeze. 
this couldnâ€™t be happening to you. 
you stand there. 
unable to speak. 
unable to move.
hoping it passes. 
when it does 
eventually pass, 
youâ€™re confused. 
angry. 
ashamed. 
that shame is yours. 
because you didnâ€™t do something about it. 
you couldnâ€™t. 
itâ€™s your fault. 
you silly girl. 
this is my experience with sexual harassment. 
my story is nothing remarkable.
it is a collection of these moments.
they are all too common
and silently shared by many.

__________________________________ i can trace a number of these moments when i was made to feel less than. not to the fault of the individuals, but the society and ideas that shaped them. these moments of mine vary in intensity and have taken anywhere from a day to 8 years to process. some may have yet to even surface. iâ€™ve started reclaiming myself and my femininity by learning through the stories of others that iâ€™m not crazy and iâ€™m not alone. itâ€™s much bigger than any one of us. and thereâ€™s power in the collection of moments. 
so over the next few weeks iâ€™ll be writing and sharing them with you. whether youâ€™re on the accidental cause or receiving end of a similar moment, what i hope is that you know youâ€™re not alone. its not your fault. and that you can do something about it. .
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
rajkumar hirani accused of sexual assault, he denies

filmmaker rajkumar hirani has been accused of sexual assault by a woman who worked with him in his 2018 film "sanju". he has denied the allegation.

according to a huffpost india article on sunday, the woman claimed that hirani sexually abused her on more than one occasion over a six-month period between march and september 2018. 
the 56-year-old filmmaker has denied the allegations. a statement issued by his lawyer anand desai dubbed the allegations "false", "mischievous", "scandalous", "motivated" and "defamatory". for more news and updates, subscribe to www.english.mathrubhumi.com

text:
hi... i'm andrea nicole. an artist, a creator, a curator of all things beautiful, singer-songwriter, a lover, a fighter, a believer, business owner, a daughter and a friend. the journey leading up to this moment has been a movie.... something similar to the fast and furious. agonizing lows,  with ongoing highs.... continuous shots of adrenaline that kept me alert and afloat. i knew there was no stopping, i knew there was no point in giving up. i'd come too far and was lost in a vault that only i had the key to. music is what my life started with, i was never too fashionable. music is my gift, music is my comfort. fashion came like a thief in the night.... silently... growing into a monster i became prisoner to. i became prisoner to my own expression.... weird right? it wasn't planned...it really wasn't planned. 2018 was good to me. 2019 will be the reality i create, the one i always wanted, the one i've dreamed of.... not the one i became prisoner to. i'll activate my love for music all over again.... i'll share with you the deepest parts of my being, the things i can't express thru clothing or pictures..... just music. music is where i started... music is where i'll end.
blessings.... thanks  @teenvogue for the feature! #keepgoing #motivation #dontstop #perseverance #livestrong #selfcare #holistic #bewell #dontgiveup #live #laugh #love #muterkelly #metoo #survivor #cancersucks #heal #healer #westindian #roots #heritage #ancestral #payhomage #rituals #lovewins #naturalhair #queen #yourmajesty

through the centerâ€™s professional training program, we work with you to enhance your staffâ€™s understanding of the dynamics of intimate partner violence and develop your competency for responding safely and compassionately to clients, patients, or co-workers who have experienced intimate partner violence or sexual assault.

to inquire about the centerâ€™s professional training services and fees, complete the form with the link in bio or call 502-581-7208. you can also contact the training team through training@cwfempower.org.

"for the first time in its 127-year history, the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys â€” and the document features a warning.
â€œtraditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit malesâ€™ psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health,â€ the report warns.

the new â€œguidelines for psychological practice with boys and menâ€ defines â€œmasculinity ideologyâ€ as â€œa particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewal of the appearance of weakness.â€ the report links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part, too. he recommended they let their boys know, â€œitâ€™s ok to not be ok all the time.â€'
--tim fitzsimons, @nbcnews

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
bit of an exaggeration, and in reality both scenarios are worthy of #criticism 
still, this is very much relevant in the age of #metoo 
i for one have certainly been told to be #flattered when women have groped me, and even been #accused of being #gay when expressing discomfort and disinterest. 
so concluding that #harassment somehow is a product of #toxicmasculinity and the #patriarchy simply isn't right. 
now some might jump in and say that being groped and called gay is nothing compared to being raped, and you are of course right. you will also be right in pointing out that women are more often victims of rape than men. 
what i question is that this is somehow due to gender beyond the fact that men usually are physically stronger than women and therefore are in a"better" position to defend themselves. 
as a male victim of mental and physical abuse from a female ex, including #forced physical intimacy, i can attest to that it is a huge taboo for me as a man to tell this to anyone since i feel like i "had" the power to stop it.

this feeling is further strengthened from the fact that due to our larger physical strength, we men are in danger of looking like the abuser when defending ourselves from abusive women. 
my ex certainly didn't manage to inflict serious physical damage very often when hitting me, at least directly and in the short term. in the long term however she probably took quite some time from my life expectancy. and due her being so out of control i couldn't away from her in those moments without the fear of accidently injuring her in the process, since the only way i could get away was using superior physical strength. 
i could hold her down, but that forced me to stay and listen to her continue raging and screaming hateful words at me. if i tried to move away she'd fly at me with her hands once more! and if i tried to shove her away to gain time getting out of the apartment, she might fall over and get injured. those times i did manage to get out, i'd get bombarded with hateful texts and threats - both to socially shame me to my friends and family, which she did at multiple occasions, and suicide threats - by phone and messaging.

text_retweet:
*trigger warning, queens.  i was in my feelings this morning* i know i am late posting about this but wanted to express joy for the clemency of this young woman. at the same time, i am tearfully experiencing rage and sadness that she has served so many years of her life in this heinous system for fighting back against a crime against her body, her soul, and her humanity. rage is what i feel!!! there are daily reminders of how dishonored, abused, traumatized, etc. women's bodies (particularly black and brown) have been for centuries in this world. how little concern is shown even within our own community - the victim shaming and blaming, the numerous cases we will never hear about, those women and girls who suffer, process, self-hate, and further self-oppress because it is what they know. as someone who has experienced sexual trauma at the super young age of 3, i know it can become a part of you, show up in your life in the most unexpected ways. we push back everyday against conditioning that says that our bodies are for others to get a fix, a receptacle for another's toxic energy. navigating a misogynistic ideology that trains us that the exploitation and oppression of women is "just the way it is." the irony and the sadness is that humanity began in the very womb-niverse that now is so taken for granted, invalidated and abused. my soul tells me that once we all take a stand for the sacredness of the black woman's body, the symbol of the original mother of all, we will see a major shift and expansion of love in the world. i continue my spiritual, transformational work grounded in this purpose. my mission is our liberation. from my open-heart filled with love to yours. in a world that tells you otherwise, remember your queen-status as you breathe. ase.â €

text:
veel te veel vrouwen zijn slachtoffer van seksueel misbruik. door de #metoo beweging beginnen we te zien hoe veel die ellende voorkomt. het merendeel van die vrouwen wordt, in ieder geval in eerste instantie, niet geloofd. het slachtoffer wordt voor leugenaar uitgemaakt tenzij ze met hard bewijs komt. (en vaak daarna alsnog.) ik vindt dat we slachtoffers gewoon kunnen geloven. schuld en strafmaat zijn zaken voor het juridisch systeem. 
#seksueelmisbruik #believewomen

text:
i always thought that my voice was smaller in the presence of everyone until i noticed that it was only smaller because i had allowed it to be. now, i say what i say and i mean it. i am not afraid to speak my mind and sometimes my mind is not what you expect. my mind is the raw thoughts that most are afraid to say. lately the thing that tells you not to say something, thatâ€™s broken. i broke it because i wanted to be heard. its exhausting keeping every thought to yourself, and frankly, i am tired of being tired. i want to be powerful. i always craved the day that i would be strong enough to stand tall. now that i do stand taller than i ever could have imagined. i now stand too tall for anyone to walk over me like a doormat, for them to make me feel small with hurtful words and cruel rumours. i took my life and started running. i never could have imagined i would run this far, and darlingâ€¦i donâ€™t plan on ever stopping.

text:
mgtow 101: alpha female/male traits â€” vulnerability

in the perfect world with the perfect girl a man can be completely vulnerable with his woman. now a days a man almost has to be completely cold with his woman. this picture speaks volumes. the strongest men needs the strongest women and by strongest i mean the most feminine, vulnerable and nurturing.
ğŸ‘‚
ğŸ‘‚
vulnerability in a woman is the ultimate sign of femininity and womanhood. a girl who doesn't open up because she doesn't want to get hurt is still a little girl who has yet to master her emotions. a woman who is still feminine and healthy hearted will allow herself to be completely vulnerable to the right man. vulnerability means trust, a willingness to grow, it means she needs you and most importantly it is a trait of an emotionally stable and mature women.
ğŸ‘‚
ğŸ‘‚
females that don't want to open up avoid vulnerability like accountability. a feminine women makes no mistake, that she needs a man. a masculine women makes it clear she does not need a man. the masculine beta female uses this mask to avoid being vulnerable while the feminine women opens up and embraces her vulnerability because her feelings aren't swayed by whether the man is sincere or not, her feelings are mastered and don't control her.
ğŸ‘‚
ğŸ‘‚
the four characters of manhood are the warrior (protector), the monk (guidance), the negotiator and the lover. these are all the four traits that embody each man. if a woman says she doesn't need us to protect her, guide her, lead her nor love her, then how can he operate as a real man with her. ladies femininity, submissiveness, vulnerability will all attract men to you like a magnet.

"for the first time in its 127-year history, the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys â€” and the document features a warning.
â€œtraditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit malesâ€™ psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health,â€ the report warns.

the new â€œguidelines for psychological practice with boys and menâ€ defines â€œmasculinity ideologyâ€ as â€œa particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewal of the appearance of weakness.â€ the report links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part, too. he recommended they let their boys know, â€œitâ€™s ok to not be ok all the time.â€'
--tim fitzsimons, @nbcnews

text:
yaa asantewaa was born october 17, 1840 and she died october 17, 1921.
she was queen mother of ejisu in the ashanti empire â€“ now part of modern-day ghana, appointed by her brother nana akwasi afrane opese, the edwesuhene, or ruler, of edwesu.
in 1900 she led the ashanti war known as the war of the golden stool, also known as the yaa asantewaa war, against british colonialism.
beginning in march 1900, the rebellion laid siege to the fort at kumasi where the british had sought refuge.
the fort still stands today as the kumasi fort and military museum.
during the fighting, queen yaa asantewaa and fifteen of her closest advisers were captured, and they, too, were sent into exile to the seychelles.
the rebellion represented the final war in the anglo-asante series of wars that lasted throughout the 19th century.
on 1 january 1902 the british were finally able to accomplish what the asante army had denied them for almost a century, and the asante empire was made a protectorate of the british crown.
she is seen by ghanaians today as a queen mother who exercised her political and social clout to help defend her kingdom.
the experience of seeing a woman serving as political and military head of an empire was foreign to british colonial troops in 19th-century africa.
yaa asantewaa's call upon the women of the asante empire is based on the political obligations of akan women and their respective roles in legislative and judicial processes.
to highlight the importance of encouraging more female leaders in ghanaian society, the yaa asantewaa girls' secondary school was established at kumasi in 1960 with funds from the ghana education trust.

7 months ago i was raped, this is something i have not openly talked about but iâ€™m ready to share my story. this is by far the most traumatic experience that has ever happened to me and this is something i have to battle with everyday. i had people judge me saying â€œwhat were you wearing?â€, â€œwere you drinking?â€, â€œyou put yourself in that situationâ€, â€œyou should of just fought back harderâ€, â€œyouâ€™re lyingâ€. people are ashamed to come out about this issue but i am not ashamed and will not let it define me. i had the right to drink, i had the right to dress however i wanted and i had the right to go for a walk. but i did not have the right to be raped. how someone can strip away my self-worth, my safety and my happiness layer by layer until their was nothing left of me, i will never understand. i have hope that one day rape culture will change but for now we need to start teaching people not to rape and to not automatically blame the victim. it is only now that i have fully learned to except and love my body and to not see it as a wound. i am hoping my story spreads more awareness of this issue as it happens far too often and to let others know that iâ€™m here to talk and for support. i am not what happened to me, i am what i choose to become. â€¢

"for the first time in its 127-year history, the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys â€” and the document features a warning.
â€œtraditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit malesâ€™ psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health,â€ the report warns.

the new â€œguidelines for psychological practice with boys and menâ€ defines â€œmasculinity ideologyâ€ as â€œa particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewal of the appearance of weakness.â€ the report links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part, too. he recommended they let their boys know, â€œitâ€™s ok to not be ok all the time.â€'
--tim fitzsimons, @nbcnews

text: in the wee hours of this sunday morning i find myself being visited by my depression. i have learned to cope by personifying her. she takes on the form of 18 year old me, overwhelmed with fear and pain and no skills to process her intense emotions. she lashes out and tries to bring others down. i'm here for her when she occasionally visits and try to brighten her day (which brightens mine as well). she haunts me like a sad, lost spirit. i hope someday my patience and love for her, for myself, will give her the courage she needs to move on. #chooselove #depression #mentalhealthawareness #copingskills #insomnia  #haunted #loveyourself #metoo

text:
thoughts/opinions?
.
.
.
"for the first time in its 127-year history, the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys â€” and the document features a warning. â€œtraditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit malesâ€™ psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health,â€ the report warns.

the new â€œguidelines for psychological practice with boys and menâ€ defines â€œmasculinity ideologyâ€ as â€œa particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewal of the appearance of weakness.â€ the report links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part, too. he recommended they let their boys know, â€œitâ€™s ok to not be ok all the time.â€'
--tim fitzsimons, @nbcnews

via @theconsciouskid

her soul is this fire, warm with a comforting glow yet formidable, fire that was once the pride of the gods, stolen from them for man. she is the flame that warms the cold nights and brings light to the dark passages. like fire she gives, and like fire she can incinerate. she may be the candle struggling to burn on a windy night, she may be the warmth of the hearth turning your house into a home. she may be the flame dancing gracefully on a cold night or she may be the blaze that reminds you fire is not be played with....whatever she is or whatever she hopes to be, her soul has been, and will always be, fire.... #hearmetoo #motivation #humanrights  #metoo #genderequality #violenceagainstwomen #women #standup #childmarriage #sexual #physicalabuse #feminist #humanrightsforall #wellbeing #heforshe #bhfyp #domesticviolence #unwomen  #timesup #sisterhood #womenempowerment #whyididntreport #genderbasedviolence  #sexism #flame #fearlessgirl #femmesbattues #successfulwomen  #positivevibes

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

i have never been the type of person to wanna be a leader.  and tbh iâ€™m not really sure iâ€™d be any good at it, especially when i already have a hard time leading my own life.  how and why would anybody wanna lead a movement, lead a people, lead a cause when they know just how flawed, how imperfect, how not-quite-ready they felt about themselves?  and we know this is the case...mlk, gandhi, rosa parks, bell hooks etc....all incredible leaders but iâ€™m sure even these human rightsâ€™ giants had there moments....moments where they probably didnâ€™t feel theyâ€™d be good leaders at all. but i guess it was the injustices they saw that made them mad enough, moved enough, inspired enough to wanna step up and fight against them.  they became our leaders...cuz they had to.
.
.
but i think what makes a good leader is not whether he or she feels they be any good at it.  i guess it has to be the cause, the movement, the people that matter more.  this is true when it comes to changing the world ğŸŒ but i think itâ€™s also true about being the leaders of our own lives.  and whether itâ€™s music, being a parent, a student, a social justice warrior, or just a human being in general...we already have the qualities it takes to be great leaders of our lives...all of us.  and tho itâ€™s great to fight against the injustices of the the world but the injustices in our own lives are just as bad...self-doubt, guilt, shame, all of it is a real threat.  and we may not feel like leaders but maybe when we feel mad enough, moved enough, inspired enough weâ€™ll step up and fight for control of our own lives.  and maybe then weâ€™ll become the kind of leaders we need for our own lives...cuz we have to. âœŠğŸ¾ğŸ’œ #loveyourself
.

text:
i am finally starting to feel hopeful and empowered and currently trying to repress that near-instinctual thought telling me "you don't deserve to be happy" and "don't get too comfortable." once in a while, i catch myself doing things that are self-sabotaging. i have some deep subconscious belief that i don't deserve to beÂ happy, so i try and make that come to fruition. however, the difference now is that i actually catch myself and don't fall into these habits anymore. i deserve to be happy.Â youÂ deserve to be happy. it is absolutely our birthright and anytime that voice in your head suggests otherwise, you must say to it: bullshit. 
so i am going to allow myself to feel hopeful and empowered. i deserve this feeling.

text:
i hope rkelly gets the help and rehabilitation he needs. as black people we are too easily led.
we don't protect our own.
we don't respect our own.
this disgusts me as much as the allegations against this man.
i haven't been able to watch the #survivingrkelly documentary yet 
unfortunately as there's profit involved it's not available to watch for free on youtube.
i've watched many interviews though and the question in my mind is ../at what point does a "victim" stop being a victim and starts to become a predator, and conversely at what point does a "predator" stop being a predator and starts to become a victim?
.
.
.
this man has made some of the best music from any generation so i will not #muterkelly you can fuck right off with that.
.
.
i believe if he's guilty he will have his day in court.
i want to see healing among all the parties and i want to see him confront these allegations like a man and take the steps needed to fix his life and the situation.
(if this means we have to order in sex dolls from japan so be it.)
on a serious note, i think this #metoo movement is toxic and reverse sexism and i will be glad to see the end of it.
if you're interested in the way i think and would like to read more about my views on the situation - click the link in the bio.
#godsavetheking (@therealtank, @johnlegend @jadapinkettsmith this is how you should have reacted)

text:
chicagoland hometown radio station 95.1 refuses to play r.kelly @rkelly music!  @lamontwatts

according to celebrity insider, 95.1 a radio station in chicago join two other  dallas radio stations in refusal to play r. kelly music due a recent 6 series documentaries special aired on lifetime special, "surviving r.kelly". the documentary speaks with several of his victims and goes into details about r. kelly's past such his childhood, relationships(personal, professional and sexually), career and criminal background to make connection. 
lamont watts, @lamontwatts who runs 95.1 posted on a video on facebook explaining their reasons for following suit. he says, â€œi donâ€™t want to pass judgment, i just look at women at a larger scale. this is bigger, bigger than the women who were saying something about the r. kelly situation,â€ watts said. â€œas you look at both sides and everything going on, and the #metoo movement, we felt it was the right thing to do.â€ here is our two cents on this
i cannot in good conscience continue to listen to r.kelly music knowingly that those songs were written about a damn child! 
i want to give a show out to @95.1clubsteppinchicago for taking corporate responsibility and looking for their communities. also, i  want to give another shout to the two dallas radio stations @krnb1057, @claudiajordan and @k104fm
who started the movement.

text:
assigned to my bed, iâ€™ve watched clips from last nights golden globe awards (movies and tv being the ultimate in artistic collaboration). iâ€™ve paid attention to the shift in diversity of award winners, and celebrate it! what bothers me is the change in the statue itself this year from a global idea sitting on a square base of solidity, into an obviously more phallic symbol of power being put directly into the hands of womenâ€”subtle, confusing and somewhat disturbing. 
iâ€™ve also had time to binge on netflix and â€œthe kominsky methodâ€ which i lovedâ€” it incorporates all adult ages. as an aging woman, a year younger than michael douglas who is 74 (born the year of the monkey same as my ex-husband), there is a big emotional connection. this show is the closest portrayal to the truth of aging, the solidarity of best friends, and grief that iâ€™ve seen. itâ€™s written with humor and grace by chuck lorre and an excellent crew of writers. these two men both deserved their golden globe awards last night. 
as a writer, i am intrigued with chuck lorre who began his career as a musician. â€œplaying music impacted on the way i listen to words. there's rhythm in dialogue; there's pauses like there's rests in music. there's pauses that make comedy possible. everything plays almost musically, but with words.â€ â€”chuck lorre
when i saw lorreâ€™s tag at the end of his tv production with the following quote i see more media shift taking place, and celebrate it. contemplate this:

this was a really fun read that i was on the library waiting list for awhile. iâ€™m not usually one for memoirs, but busy made for an enjoyable ride through her tumultuous teenage years and beyond. i guess this is the purpose of most memoirs, or a byproduct of them, but she seemed so down to earth. definitely a post #metoo book, and it was cool to hear her reminisce about her time with stars like colin hanks and michelle williams. freaks and geeks is such a beloved show to me, and i havenâ€™t seen her in much of anything else, but now iâ€™m inclined to seek some of her shows out. itâ€™s not gonna change my life, but i think thatâ€™s okay.

"for the first time in its 127-year history, the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys â€” and the document features a warning.
â€œtraditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit malesâ€™ psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health,â€ the report warns.

the new â€œguidelines for psychological practice with boys and menâ€ defines â€œmasculinity ideologyâ€ as â€œa particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewal of the appearance of weakness.â€ the report links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part, too. he recommended they let their boys know, â€œitâ€™s ok to not be ok all the time.â€'
--tim fitzsimons, @nbcnews

text:
"on its own, a computer is not afraid to be turned off or malfunctional, but the human mind is, and this fear of death and ailment has been enabling our psyche throughout our days in the african savanna to stay alert and avoid possible predatory attacks by all means. and we had been living with this sense of fearful alertness for so long, that substantial traces of it still remain in our neurobiology, which get activated when we watch horror movies â€“ and that fear response gives us a certain amount of thrill, that pumps our body with adrenaline. this is the reason why many of us enjoy a good horror movie despite the fact that it may follow a sleep-less night or a sleep full of nightmares. we enjoy being on the edge because thatâ€™s how our primal ancestors spent their lives.

now here is a question to ponder over â€“ can we create a computer that can feel actual fear when there is an outbreak of a computer virus! the most we can do, is to install an anti-virus program into the system, so that if a known virus attacks it, the firewall will get activated and prevent any substantial harm to the system. but if it is a newly programmed virus, then the computer would become completely helpless, but again, it will not feel afraid or helpless, rather it will simply crash or stop functioning properly due to the infection.

artificial intelligence is nowhere near attaining actual sentience or awareness. and without awareness itâ€™s simply a mechanical device, which may pretend to show emotions and sentience, if it is programmed to do so, and thus it may be able to fool the humans as being alive, but in its own internal circuitry, itâ€™d simply be following algorithm." read full piece here: naskarism.wordpress.com

journey into the literary universe of the celebrated humanitarian neuroscientist and international bestselling author abhijit naskar.

text:
14th of december

25 years ago today! twenty five years!
...
a lifetime ago. a whole different world!
...
twenty five years ago today i moved in with my abuser, my biological father at 13 years old

it is the first year that the weight of this day does not lay heavily on my shoulders!

i held myself responsible for not listening to my original gut instinct all those years ago as did my mother for "leaving her"

but that new jigsaw price allowed me to realise, decisions had been made in my life out with my control that led to that moment, decisions that as a mother i can put hand on my heart and say 'i would never have made'

this year i pass the weight of that day 25 yrs ago back on her shoulders! where they should have been all these years, no loving remorseful mother would have allowed her daughter to bare the weight of her mistakes so willingly and insistently! *** #fortitude
#fortitudeproject

#abusesurvivor
#childhoodtrauma
#childsexualabuse

text: to say that 2018 was a rollercoaster ride would be a callous understatement. we saw the best and worst that humanity had to offer. we bore witness to some of the most devastating humanitarian and environmental crises in recent history. our country is in turmoil, our planet is in crisis, our president embroiled in scandal and is a lesson in incompetence. 2018 also brought light and hope. we saw lawyers and activists defend refugees at our border, we saw abusers held accountable for their actions, we saw courageous women speak out against those abusers, we saw children fight for their right to live without the fear of being shot in their schools, we saw journalists stand up to power in search of the truth, we saw citizens organized, mobilized and inspired to make their voices heard at the polls. we marched, donated, called, protested, and fought for the values we share and must continue to fight to protect. it was an honor to be a small part of those achievements. and for the first time in a couple of years, i am excited about the future, for i expect that we will see this light shine even brighter in 2019. leonard cohen said it best, â€œthere is a crack in everything, thatâ€™s how the light gets in.â€ #2019 i welcome you.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the repo include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a pa, too. he recommended they let their boys know, â€œitâ€™s ok to not be ok all the time.â€'
--tim fitzsimons, bcnews

repost from @theconsciouskid using @repostregramapp - "for the first time in its 127-year history, the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys â€” and the document features a warning.
â€œtraditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit malesâ€™ psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health,â€ the report warns.

the new â€œguidelines for psychological practice with boys and menâ€ defines â€œmasculinity ideologyâ€ as â€œa particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewal of the appearance of weakness.â€ the report links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part, too. he recommended they let their boys know, â€œitâ€™s ok to not be ok all the time.â€'
--tim fitzsimons, @nbcnews

text:
â¬…ï¸â¬…ï¸â¬…ï¸â¬…ï¸â¬…ï¸ swipe left

these are all characteristics of a perpetrator = an immoral person. i don't post these just to post them. i post because i have true and raw experiences of domestic violence. i am not scared to speak my truth.  love might be blind, but set aside your feelings and take a step back and look at the big picture. it's hard to see a wolf in sheep's clothing but the signs are there. he will come off extremely charming, doing anything for you. you'll confide in him about your past struggles and pain (he will eventually use this against you). once he has manipulated you into feeling sorry for him, he has you where he wants you. in his comfort zone, in his environment where he knows he can control you. he will cross boundaries by envading your privacy - go though your phone, emails, ig, fb. once he has gathered the information he needs to use against you he'll keep it to himself. he won't let you know that he holds the information but he'll be completely passive aggressive with you while you're feeling confused as to why he's acting like that. he'll get drunk and lost in his thoughts and then lash out on you. accuse you of sleeping with other people. but you're emotionally in too deep and can't pull away. verbal abuse eventually turns into physical abuse and now you feel stuck. he will apologize over and over again and promise to change. you will go round and round in the cycle of abuse. it's like a merry go round that never stops until you say enough is enough. 
don't let it get to this! pay attention to the signs! be smart!

text:
finally watched surviving r kelly last night. i went into it knowing the subject matter might prove triggering but i'm very glad i did. 
as a survivor of an emotionally, psychologically, (& at the end physically) abusive relationship, these women's stories rang so true! you could see the truth of their stories in their stiffened body language, hear it in their voices cracking with emotion, see it in the sparkle-turned-to-deadpan looks in their eyes. 
the strength of these survivors blows me away & i'm still haunted by their words, expressions, and stories 12+ hours later & doubt that haunted feeling will leave me any time soon. 
i'm glad that somebody made this film to continue to shed light onto kelly's monstrosities. and i can only hope this added attention and the pressure from this film & the protest movements surrounding it can continue until he slips up & can be brought to justice. big props to the groups working towards that goal & working to boycott kelly throughout the country. 
my heart both breaks & goes out to the women still trapped in his web. i know that it isn't as easy as "just leaving" him & i truly hope those women can find, through the fog of abuse, the power inside themselves to get out & to heal themselves. it is a long, difficult but indefineably valuable road. i hope they can re-find their brightness & strength. ğŸ’™ 
and because i'm not one to ignore such an obviously important intersection: fellow white activist women & feministsâ€”i'm surprised i haven't seen much from you regarding this!! y'all were posting constantly about the metoo movement when the weinstein stories broke...but hardly a post/share about this. 
we need to do better. you can start by watching this docuseries, by valuing & recognizing the validity of the black women sharing their horrific stories. if you were outraged by weinstein, then you ought to be outraged by kelly too. 
____________________________
