"for the first time in its 127-year history, the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys â€” and the document features a warning.
â€œtraditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit malesâ€™ psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health,â€ the report warns.

the new â€œguidelines for psychological practice with boys and menâ€ defines â€œmasculinity ideologyâ€ as â€œa particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewal of the appearance of weakness.â€ the report links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part, too. he recommended they let their boys know, â€œitâ€™s ok to not be ok all the time.â€'
--tim fitzsimons, @nbcnews

text: *trigger warning* || when an adult forces themselves upon a child that child is irrevocably altered. a vortex of shame, guilt, disorientation and alienation persists long after trauma has passed. their once familiar body feels foreign. they can't remember how it got there but they know in their bones it isn't theirs. it feels as if that stolen skin suit they are wearing is transparent. they feel at once perpetually on display and hidden where noone can find them. their heart is either bleeding or vacant. they wonder if they could have stopped it, if they somehow invited it and what it means if their body responded in some way to the violent invasion they endured. everyone who meets them can see their organs. people don't know why it makes them uneasy they only know that it does. when a grown-up forces themselves upon a child they irrevocably alter them. this is what this image in the series is about. the confusion, the rage, the sadness, the hiding, the questioning and eventually... the healing. i am not the woman i could have been. it has taken me a long time to say that and even longer to accept it. i am not the woman i could have been but the woman i am is resilient, resourceful and healing. and right now that is enough. || studio assist @benmayhew ||

text: i have a warning to all local women living in the rohnert park area. i was out walking my dog and had forgotten to refill my bags. prince pooped on a well-maintained lawn because i wasnâ€™t paying attention. i decided to walk around the block, stop home for bags, and then walk by the house again to pick up what prince had left. i made it maybe two houses down when a white man with short brown hair, about 5â€™6â€, caught up with me. he was yelling, without letting me answer or get away, about how all the dogs shit on his lawn, that he has three kids (donâ€™t know how thatâ€™s related), and how would i like it if he came and shat on my lawn. he repeated these three points to me rapid-fire. it was impossible to get a word in. having been a victim of mild harassment working in customer service over the years, i tried to use what i had learned. i calmly explained that i was going to return home to get bags and that i had run out. he got closer to me and continued yelling, so i crossed the street to give myself distance and began walking in the opposite direction. he then followed me for about a half block while screaming that he was going to shit on my lawn. i was certain he would follow me home, so i again explained that i would be back to pick it up. luckily, he did cease following me. i made it home relatively unshaken, mostly just amazed at how angry people could get. i went back and picked up the poop and walked around the block. i thought about this manâ€™s kids and the example he was setting for them involving conflict resolution (his son had come to the edge of the yard.) i thought that maybe this man was having a hard day as a parent, as a homeowner, and that maybe if i went back and apologized it would clear up any future neighborly conflict. mostly i wanted his kids to see how the situation should have been handled. i knocked on his door, he answered, and i asked him if he was ready to listen to me. he remained silent, so i started to explain that i was sorry and that i make an effort to always pick up after my dog. i told him he lives on a busy street (adrian) with lots of dog walkers and that some are bound to be irresponsible. (contâ€™d in comments)

text:
trigger warning***
i love hiking, i love running, and i love being outside. one of my favourite things about living in ontario is easy access to the bruce trail. if i could be out there every single day, i would be in heaven. 
until this summer. 
i was running by myself on a very heavily trafficked trail, enjoying the sunshine and the trees, without a care in the world. as i was running, i found myself surrounded by a group of young men (at least 8 or 9 of them), who decided that it was appropriate to make me feel very uncomfortable and threatened by their hyper-sexualized comments, and body language. i was so uncomfortable, and felt so unsafe ( even though in this particular encounter i was not physically harmed), that i stopped going out on my own completely. 
i am so disappointed and angry that the new generation of males still think this is acceptable behaviour. i have been so angry that something i love was ruined for me. and i have been furious that i am still afraid. 
but i am tired of being afraid. so, my special someone has equipped me with some new tools to take back what i love. 
i feel for anyone, men and women, who have been made to feel unsafe, and to have the things you love tainted by fear. 
no more for me. i am tired of being afraid. i am tired of losing out and avoiding what i love because of others, and being intimidated. no longer will i be quiet, and no longer will i accept this as "the way things are". #recoverycoach #real #recovery #metoo #safe #mentalhealth #strongwomen #feminist #getoutsideandplay

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.
